<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com<item><title><![CDATA[Fossil fuel investment ‘very unwise economic risk’, says energy expert]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/14/fossil-fuel-investment-very-unwise-economic-risk-energy-expert-fatih-birol]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T05:00:20Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/2ba80025d17f73b17464d7ad645d435bfb736035/0_27_5000_2999 /master/5000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=089eb694171199918169e3271562584e&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;唐宁街的气候抗议者&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;计划扩大化石燃料生产的国家和公司正在采取行动世界上最重要的能源顾问警告说，“非常不健康和不明智的经济风险”，因为他们的投资可能无法盈利。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;国际能源署 (IEA) 执行董事法提赫·比罗尔 (Fatih Birol) 本周预测， &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/12/beginning-of-the-end-of-fossil-fuel-era-approaching-says-iea&quot;>;化石燃料将达到峰值这十年&lt;/a>;是气候的历史性转折点。但尽管需求可能下降，并且面临气候混乱的威胁，许多国家和私营部门公司仍在考虑新产能。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;比罗尔表示：“新的大型化石燃料项目不仅带来重大气候风险，还有公司及其投资者的商业和财务风险。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“当我与石油公司（无论是国际石油公司还是国内石油公司）交谈时，他们中的一些人说我们一直在石油和石油领域投资不足。气体。但公司和投资者应该对这种说法非常小心，并牢记我们所看到的需求轨迹。这可能会导致他们承担非常不健康、不明智的经济和气候风险。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;政府应该紧急&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/09/ Phase-out-fossil-fuels-cop-28-un-summit-coal-oil-gas&quot;>;在 Cop28 上讨论逐步淘汰化石燃料&lt;/a>;，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www. theguardian.com/environment/2023/jun/02/window-close-cop28-change-course-climate-dubai&quot;>;即将举行的联合国气候峰会&lt;/a>;，比罗尔说。逐步淘汰的问题是&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2022/nov/20/deal-on-loss-and-damage-fund-at-cop27-marks-climbdown-by -rich-countries&quot;>;去年的缔约方会议排名下降&lt;/a>;，但许多国家计划今年重新引发辩论。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;77262ea87a0a87a583fbdbef3494baa481c4ed1e&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https: //media.guim.co.uk/77262ea87a0a87a583fbdbef3494baa481c4ed1e/160_0_3271_2742/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Fatih Birol&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;838&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;法提赫·比罗尔表示公司和国家误判了市场趋势和人们的情绪。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;摄影：Simon Maina/AFP/Getty&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;但即使政府当前的气候政策，比罗尔指出，如果资源不足且需要加强，全球所需的石油和天然气数量将会下降。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“如果你今天开始一个项目，无论你身在何处，第一批石油或天然气将进入市场五年后，全球石油和天然气趋势将下降，”他在接受《卫报》采访时表示。 “因此，人们不仅应该非常小心气候风险，还应该非常谨慎地关注大型油气项目的商业风险。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;比罗尔拒绝点名任何国家，但提到了几个发达国家和发展中国家。尽管各经济体承诺将全球气温上升限制在比工业化前水平高1.5摄氏度的范围内，但它们仍在计划大规模扩大化石燃料生产。美国本周被发现&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/12/us-behind-more-than-a-third-of-global-oil-and -gas-expansion-plans-report-finds&quot;>;规划从现在到 2050 年全球石油和天然气扩张的最大份额&lt;/a>;，英国政府作为首相计划发放数十个新的石油和天然气许可证，&lt; a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jul/31/dismay-as-rishi-sunak-vows-to-max-out-uk-fossil-fuel-reserves&quot;>;Rishi Sunak，发誓要“最大限度地利用”北海&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/ 2023/sep/13/fossil-fuel-companies-britain-international-charter-treaty&quot;>;化石燃料公司拥有秘密武器。以下是英国可以如何帮助他们夺走这种权利的方法 | Cleodie Rickard&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;一些计划扩张的国家和公司引用了 IEA 的调查结果，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2021/may /18/no-new-investment-in-fossil-fuels-demands-top-energy-economist&quot;>;即使世界达到温室气体净零排放，未来仍然需要石油和天然气&lt;/a>;，作为他们计划的理由。比罗尔警告说，他们没有采纳国际能源署的全部建议：“未来几年我们肯定会需要石油和天然气，但问题是我们在全球范围内需要的石油和天然气数量会越来越少。” &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他说：“他们错误地判断了市场趋势——他们相信自己愿意相信的东西。就气候变化而言，他们还错误地判断了街上人们的情绪以及他们的责任。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;比罗尔对将全球可再生能源产能提高三倍的拟议承诺表示赞赏，&lt;a href=&quot;https ://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jun/07/un-climate-talks-might-avoid-fossil-fuel-phase-out-says-cop28-official&quot;>;可能成为 Cop28 的核心内容&lt; /a>;，将于 11 月底在迪拜举行。但他表示，这一承诺还不够，化石燃料的迅速减少也是将世界温升控制在 1.5 摄氏度之内所必需的。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“可再生能源的增加是好事，但在化石燃料没有减少的情况下，燃料，对温度轨迹的影响将很小或没有，”他说。 “应该[在第 28 届缔约方大会上讨论逐步淘汰化石燃料]。我希望讨论能够向市场发出化石燃料消耗将会下降的信号。”比罗尔表示，可再生能源价格可能上涨的警告有些过头了。 “（价格）可能会出现一些波动，但总体趋势是它们（与化石燃料）具有竞争力，并且未来将更具竞争力，”他说。 “太阳能非常有竞争力，海上风电正在取得重大进展 - 很快我们就会看到它也具有竞争力。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;尽管他预测化石燃料的使用将在本十年内首次达到峰值，比罗尔说各国政府还需要做更多的工作，以确保其使用量随后大幅下降。 “最重要的问题不是峰值，而是峰值后化石燃料的下降，这是问题的神经中枢。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;当前的政策将导致全球升温2.4℃，必须加以解决。他说，作为紧急事项，加强了力度。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 13:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia-Ukraine war live: drones attack Russian Black sea ships for second day; Boris Johnson blasts UK policy on war]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/sep/14/russia-ukraine-war-live-updates-drones-attack-russian-black-sea-fleet-boris-johnson-blasts-uk-policy-latest-news]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T05:19:39Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/40eed2f59373d28814c3304a1fc084ee435b94bb/0_0_5760_3840 /master/5760.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7bb7b9cc7d9e2bbbd4e97309de2e3024&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;乌克兰战俘亲属集会，要求在基辅进行更多战俘交换。&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 13:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Taiwan tells Elon Musk it is ‘not for sale’ after latest China comments]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/14/taiwan-elon-musk-china-comments-response-all-in-summit-los-angeles]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T03:50:44Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/4566744cb4a283e96c739fad628cc0acadc463cb/0_0_2691_1615 /master/2691.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=5b55babdd048de57499d9143bcec63d7&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;埃隆·马斯克表示，中国可能会像美国看待夏威夷一样看待台湾。 &lt;/div>;&lt;p>;台湾外交部长严厉斥责称台湾是中国不可分割的一部分的埃隆·马斯克，称台湾是“非卖品”，再次涉足北京与台北之间的棘手问题关系。他发表此番言论之际，数十艘中国军舰和飞机被发现在台湾附近进行疑似军事演习。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;马斯克是社交媒体平台 X（前身为 Twitter）以及特斯拉电动汽车公司的亿万富翁所有者。和 SpaceX，在洛杉矶举行的 All-In 峰会上发表的评论已于本周上传到 YouTube。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“他们（北京的）政策是让台湾与中国统一。从他们的角度来看，也许它类似于夏威夷或类似的地方，就像中国不可分割的一部分，但任意地不属于中国一部分，主要是因为……美国太平洋舰队已经停止了任何形式的武力统一努力，”他说。 /p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/sep/07/elon-musks-hypocrisy-about-free -speech-hits-a-new-low&quot;>;埃隆·马斯克对言论自由的虚伪程度再创新低 |玛格丽特·沙利文&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;台湾外交部长吴钊燮在周三晚间的一篇帖子中回应称，他希望马斯克能够要求中国“向其人民开放@X”。中国封锁了X以及Facebook等其他主要西方社交媒体。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“也许他认为禁止它是一个好政策，就像关闭@Starlink以阻止乌克兰对俄罗斯的反击一样，”吴补充道，指的是马斯克的&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/sep/12/elon-musk-biographer-admits-suggestion-spacex-head-blocked-ukraine-drone-attack-was-wrong&quot; >;去年拒绝了乌克兰在克里米亚港口城市塞瓦斯托波尔启动其星链卫星网络的请求&lt;/a>;，以协助攻击那里的俄罗斯舰队。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“听着，台湾不是中华人民共和国的一部分&amp;amp;肯定不卖！”吴说，用的是中华人民共和国的缩写。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这并不是马斯克在上海拥有大型特斯拉工厂第一次激怒台湾。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;去年 10 月，他&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2022/oct/08/elon-musk-taiwan-china-special-administrative-zone-hong-kong&quot;>;表示，中国与可以通过将台湾的部分控制权移交给北京来解决台湾问题，从而招致台湾的同样强烈谴责。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;北京声称台湾是中国的一个省，习近平已承诺将其吞并，必要时可以使用武力。台湾民选政府、主要反对党以及越来越多的台湾人民拒绝接受中国统治的前景。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;作为回应，北京通过经济、外交和军事手段加大了对台湾的压力。 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/china-unveils-taiwan-economic-integration-plan-as-warships-conduct-manoeuvres-off-coast&quot;>;本周这是自4月份大型演习以来中国在台湾附近最大规模的军事活动&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国人民解放军几乎每天都派出飞机和舰船侵入台湾，频繁进入其防空识别区和跨越台湾海峡中线。周四，台湾国防部表示，在过去 24 小时内，在台湾周围发现了 68 架飞机和 10 艘船只，其中包括 40 次空中穿越中线。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;最近几天的飞行路线显示出异常活动，飞行时间更长花在台湾一侧旅行的时间，显然是在解放军航母战斗群的陪同下通过台湾南端进入西太平洋。分析人士称，第二批舰艇穿过其北端，正准备加入打击群。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;日本防卫省周三晚间报告说，解放军两艘航空母舰之一的山东号，地点位于台湾主岛西南部，靠近菲律宾。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;此次可疑的军事演习（北京或解放军尚未宣布）可能是为了回应美国最近在该地区的活动。美国和加拿大海军，以及与包括菲律宾在内的其他美国盟友的联合演习。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周三，北京国台办发言人陈斌华指责美国和台湾勾结，以加强台湾的防御能力。据《中国日报》报道，陈表示，此类举动只会增加该岛面临的危险。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;路透社为本报告提供了内容&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 12:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Experts call for global moratorium on efforts to geoengineer climate]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/14/experts-call-for-global-moratorium-on-efforts-to-geoengineer-climate]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T04:00:20Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/79562254b8fb133d58c9ce5e71b8ae6bed9a2b60/43_0_2677_1606 /master/2677.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=1be5e1fc36fdb674b36ea8b0eab0baf3&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;夕阳西下时，海滩游客沿着海滨散步&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;各国政府应暂停以下措施：随着温室气体排放持续增加和气候危机的蔓延，全球专家小组敦促对地球气候进行地球工程。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;地球工程备受争议，但随着其影响的扩大，对其可行性的讨论正在加快步伐由气候崩溃驱动的极端天气席卷了整个地球。地球工程没有全球协议，也没有关于国家或企业可以做什么的规则。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.overshootcommission.org/comingsoon&quot;>;发布的报告中周四&lt;/a>;，气候超调委员会呼吁各国政府逐步淘汰化石燃料，投入更多资源来适应极端天气的影响，并开始使用碳捕获和储存等技术来消除二氧化碳。直接从空气中提取碳。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;政府还应该允许学术界研究地球工程的可能性，主要以太阳辐射管理的形式，其中涉及尝试减少照射地球表面的阳光量，以实现可持续发展。例如，通过增白云层使其更具反射性，或在太空中设置镜子。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但专家组警告说，政府不应开展任何此类活动，因为以某种方式修补全球气候存在危险。尚不清楚。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;帕斯卡·拉米，世界贸易组织前任主席，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2022/may/17/ Climate-geoengineering-must-be-regulate-says-fore-wto-head&quot;>;担任气候超调委员会主席&lt;/a>;，表示世界温度超调 1.5 摄氏度“并非不可避免”，这是各国政府设定的全球气温上限同意，但可能性正在增加。 “这取决于我们做什么，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但他警告说，世界不能忽视地球工程的可能性，因为一些国家可能开始自行调查和实验。他说：“国际上关于太阳辐射管理的讨论越来越多。但危险是&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/aug/08/reflecting-suns-rays-would-cause-crops-to-fail-scientists-warn&quot;>;意想不到的后果以及跨界后果&lt;/a>;”。他说，科学家们无法判断太阳辐射管理是否安全，应该采用预防原则。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;拉米敦促各国政府单方面决定暂停，而不是等待全球就一项暂停协议达成一致。他在接受《卫报》采访时表示：“我不建议召开大型国际会议，根据我的经验，这会花费大量时间。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他表示，关于太阳辐射管理的学术研究应该共享，开放和透明。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;地球工程这个术语包罗万象，从大片土地重新造林以吸收更多碳，到将屋顶涂成白色以提高反光性，或者在海洋中撒铁以生长更多浮游生物和吸收更多的碳。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;气候超调委员会是一个由前高级外交官、政策专家和科学家组成的小组，其中包括前法国外交官劳伦斯·图比亚纳 (Laurence Tubiana)，他是《巴黎协定》的主要设计者之一，重点关注太阳能辐射管理，因为这是最具争议和最危险的想法之一。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;虽然重新种植树木通常被认为是安全的，但在太空中放置镜子以反射阳光或播种云以将更多光线反射到太空中可能会产生巨大影响这将很难控制，而且不可能限制在国家边界之内。除了改变一个地方的气候所固有的风险之外，还可能存在“终止冲击”——人们担心，如果在使用地球工程的同时排放继续涌入大气，停止使用该技术将导致严重破坏气候变化，因为潜在的加热效应再次出现。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;美国宇航局喷气推进实验室的气候科学家彼得·卡尔姆斯（Peter Kalmus）代表自己发言，警告了这种危险。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“地球工程、就像直接空气捕获一样，这是一种非常不确定的技术解决方案，化石燃料高管喜欢推动这种技术解决方案，以减轻其销售石油、天然气和煤炭的核心业务的压力，正如越来越多的人意识到的那样，这正在导致快速且不可逆转的情况我们星球的宜居性遭到破坏，”他告诉卫报。 “化石燃料精英将利用地球工程作为继续一切照旧的借口。作为一名气候科学家，我最糟糕的噩梦是化石燃料的持续扩张，伴随着太阳能地球工程，然后是终止冲击。对于人类文明和地球上的大部分生命来说，这将是游戏结束。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;伦敦大学学院地球系统科学教授马克·马斯林（未参与该小组）表示，许多科学家都有强烈的感受。关于地球工程。 “太阳辐射管理[努力]是危险的实验，将导致不可预测的气候变化，因为太阳能在地球上的分布是造成我们动态气候的原因，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“减少太阳能在地球上的分布一个地区将改变大气和海洋以不可预测的方式将能量从热带转移到两极的方式。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他补充道：“国际上需要强有力地暂停太阳辐射管理，以确保没有任何国家或公司试图“解决气候变化”，但会带来灾难性的后果。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/apr/25/carbon-diicide-removal-tech- Polarising-climate-science&quot;>;二氧化碳去除技术&lt;/a>;也存在争议，但争议程度远小于地球工程。该小组发现，各国应“促进快速扩大更高质量的二氧化碳清除”，包括要求化石燃料公司承担清除和储存越来越多其产品产生的碳的义务。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;迈尔斯艾伦，牛津大学地球系统科学教授，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jan/12/fossil-fuel- Producers-must-be-forced-to- take-back-carbon-say-scientists&quot;>;谁倡导碳回收义务&lt;/a>;，生产商有责任“回收”其产品中排放的二氧化碳，他说：“有了碳回收义务，我们可以在两到三十年内阻止化石燃料造成进一步的全球变暖，将未来的变暖幅度限制在低于2000年以来的变暖幅度，并使太阳辐射管理变得无关紧要。没有它，我们就不能。因此，真正的选择不是在碳回收和逐步淘汰化石燃料之间，而是在碳回收和太阳能地球工程之间。”&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href= &quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; 样式=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 12:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Libya floods: appeals for body bags amid fears of disease ‘epidemic’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/14/libya-floods-appeals-for-body-bags-disease-fears-northeastern-flooding]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T02:10:36Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3c3c9ee5b0ce8ebeb6949515355f9f3cc12961fa/0_347_5763_3495 /master/5763.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=e9c8fab214464e110649d892021a8b1d&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;周三，丹尼尔风暴在利比亚东北部德尔纳造成的破坏。由于担心疾病流行，市长呼吁人们帮助打捞尸体。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;在一场灾难性的洪水造成数千人死亡并席卷许多人之后，利比亚遭受重创的德尔纳市的救援人员呼吁提供更多裹尸袋。出海。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;自&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/12/questions-raised-over -deadly-impact-of-storm-daniel-in-libya&quot;>;风暴丹尼尔于周六晚上袭击了利比亚北部海岸。恐怕有多达 20,000 人死亡。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我们实际上需要专门负责打捞尸体的团队，”德尔纳市长 Abdulmenam al-Ghaithi 说道。 “我担心这座城市会因为废墟下和水中的大量尸体而感染流行病。”搜索小组负责人卢特菲·米斯拉蒂 (Lutfi al-Misrati) 告诉半岛电视台：“我们需要装尸体的袋子。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;早些时候，管理利比亚东部的政府民航部长希姆·阿布·奇基瓦特 (Hichem Abu Chkiouat) &lt; a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/libya-flood-death-toll&quot;>;表示“大海不断倾倒数十具尸体”&lt;/a>;。海上巡逻队正在沿海寻找被冲上岸的尸体，其中许多尸体被送往托布鲁克进行身份识别。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-atom-id=&quot;064a36c3-647b-4887-9970-26b723a15c11&quot; data-atom-type=&quot;media&quot;>; &lt;div>; &lt;div style=&quot;font-size:0&quot;>; __YOUTUBE_MEDIA_PLACEHOLDER_064a36c3-647b-4887-9970-26b723a15c11__ &lt;iframe id=&quot;gu-video-youtube-064a36c3-647b-4887 -9970-26b723a15c11&quot; src=&quot;https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/s7ZgUJkM5OE?modestbranding=1&amp;amp;showinfo=0&amp;amp;rel=0&amp;amp;enablejsapi=1&amp;amp;embed_config=%7B%22disableAds%22%3Atrue %2C%22nonPersonalizedAd%22%3Atrue%2C%22restrictedDataProcessor%22%3Atrue%2C%22adsConfig%22%3A%7B%22adTagParameters%22%3A%7B%22cmpGdpr%22%3A1%7D%7D%7D&quot;frameborder=&quot; 0&quot; allowedfullscreen>;&lt;/iframe>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;为了避免疾病传播，需要埋葬尸体，因此数百人被集中埋在一个坟墓中。德尔纳居民一直在恳求建立一座新的野战医院，因为该镇现有的两家医院已成为临时太平间。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;市长，救援队已从埃及、突尼斯、阿拉伯联合酋长国、土耳其和卡塔尔抵达盖蒂说。土耳其还派遣一艘载有设备的船只前往设立两所野战医院和 148 名医务人员，以帮助救援工作。英国周三宣布了高达 100 万英镑的初步援助计划。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;9f7bf467ab325e80ae6f2735d7cb30ea838667ba&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/9f7bf467ab325e80ae6f2735d7cb30ea838667ba/ 0_448_6720_4032/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;救援人员在德尔纳医院外运送装有遇难者遗体的尸袋。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;救援人员在德尔纳医院外运送装有遇难者遗体的尸袋。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：Mohamed Shalash/EPA&lt;/span>;总部位于的黎波里的联合国承认的民族团结政府周三表示，12个国家已向利比亚派遣了援助和救援队。其 Facebook 页面称，援助包括救援和恢复小组、追踪犬、野战医院、医疗人员、热传感设备、潜水和吸水小组、食品供应、避难所材料以及为恢复过程提供帮助的船只和飞机。&lt;/ p>; &lt;p>;盖蒂告诉沙特旗下的阿拉伯电视台，根据被洪水摧毁的地区数量，该市的死亡人数可能达到 18,000 至 20,000 人。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;洪水受害者据埃及媒体报道，包括数十名埃及移民的尸体于周三抵达开罗以南约 110 公里（68 英里）处的贝尼苏夫。人们担心，德尔纳和邻近的苏塞由于靠近意大利和希腊，成为数千名试图穿越地中海的移民的中心，其中许多人住在港口附近的简陋住房中。&lt;/p>; &lt;旁白>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/libya-floods-the-outcome-of-the-climate -crisis-meeting-a-failed-state&quot;>;利比亚的洪水是气候危机遭遇失败国家的结果&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;援助机构一直在努力抵达利比亚城市德尔纳只有超过 100,000 人因道路被毁而受阻。需要直升机，主要由埃及提供。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;前往德尔纳的利比亚记者 Mohamed Eljarh 表示，救援人员尚未到达该市的部分地区，特别是东部，以及附近的沿海城镇苏塞&lt;strong>; &lt;/strong>;和萨赫勒市。 “直到昨晚深夜，瓦砾下的一些幸存者都在发出恳求，”埃尔贾在附近的托布鲁克市告诉《卫报》。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他将苏塞和周边村庄的情况描述为“新的情况”。悲惨的一幕”。 “数百所房屋被泥土、瓦砾和水掩埋。没有任何帮助到达，”他说。 “其他地区也受到了类似的影响。死亡人数将是惊人的。”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;182a77fe50b4c6e36b90abc1ab7657686294f746&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/182a77fe50b4c6e36b90abc1ab7657686294f746/0_18 8_6000_3812/1000.jpg &quot; alt=&quot;法国士兵周三在伊斯特尔军事基地装载救灾物资飞往利比亚的货机。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;635&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;周三，法国士兵在伊斯特尔军事基地装载一架货机，向利比亚运送救灾物资。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：美联社&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;灾难发生后，52 岁的司机乌萨马·阿尔·胡萨迪 (Usama Al Husadi) 一直在寻找妻子和五个孩子。 “我步行寻找他们......我去了所有的医院和学校，但没有运气，”他双手抱头哭泣，告诉路透社。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;胡萨迪，当晚一直在工作。暴风雨，再次拨通了妻子的电话号码。它被关闭了。 “我们失去了至少 50 名我父亲的家人，有的失踪，有的死亡，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我和我的妻子幸存下来，但我失去了我的妹妹，”41 岁的 Mohamed Mohsen Bujmila 说道。老工程师说道。 “我姐姐住在市中心，大部分破坏都发生在那里。我们找到了她丈夫和儿子的尸体，并将他们埋葬了。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;路透社&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br >;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https:// feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 10:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘We’re facing another old enemy’: Rushdie warns against global authoritarianism]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/sep/13/were-facing-another-old-enemy-rushdie-warns-against-global-authoritarianism]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T01:10:50Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/296ba529a19554802f9a9bba618577cb48cf3e01/0_1_2414_1449 /master/2414.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=b383878d01ea0dffc20867616b73322a&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;一位老年白人男子的特写，留着白灰色短发和山羊胡，戴着一双戴着金属丝框眼镜，站在白色背景前。他眼镜的右镜片是黑色的。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;萨尔曼·拉什迪 (Salman Rushdie) 在费城的一个论坛上讨论威权主义威胁时，警告了全球威权主义的威胁，并表示美国共和党正在“寻求破坏”民主价值观。美国和世界各地的言论自由。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周三，拉什迪通过视频出现在全国第一修正案峰会上，将唐纳德·特朗普的崛起和英国脱欧归因于“黄金时代神话”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;拉什迪一年多前在纽约遭到袭击，他在美国继续颁布禁书令时发表了讲话。拉什迪在接受言论自由组织美国笔会首席执行官苏珊娜·诺塞尔的采访时被问及当今言论自由面临的最大威胁是什么。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/jul/12/salman-rushdie-stabbing-attack-interview&quot;>;萨尔曼·拉什迪说自从刺伤袭击后他一直在做“疯狂的梦”&lt;/a>;&lt;/ p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“如果你在 10 或 20 年前问我，我可能会说言论自由面临的主要问题源于宗教极端主义，”拉什迪说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我认为现在我们面临着另一个老敌人，那就是威权主义。我认为世界各地的独裁运动、民粹主义独裁煽动确实有所增加。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“除此之外，至少有一部分人愿意不再重视民主价值观载入第一修正案。所以我认为，我现在想说，问题是政治性的，而不是主要是宗教性的。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这次峰会由国家宪法中心主办，旨在解决对第一修正案——美国宪法权利——的威胁。言论自由——就在美国参议院就图书禁令和审查制度举行听证会的第二天。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://pen.org/press-release/media-advisory-pen- america-experts-on-book-bans-available-ahead-of-senate-hearing-9-12/&quot;>;根据美国笔会&lt;/a>;的数据，自去年秋天以来，美国已经有 4,000 多本书被禁。 2021. Pen 将图书禁令定义为学生在学校图书馆或教室中图书被视为“禁入”，或者在调查以确定是否应该实施任何限制的过程中图书被移走。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;blockquote >; &lt;p>;人们愿意不再重视第一修正案中所体现的民主价值观&lt;/p>; &lt;footer>; &lt;cite>;萨尔曼·拉什迪&lt;/cite>; &lt;/footer>; &lt;/blockquote>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p >;大多数针对性书籍都涉及种族主义、性行为和性别认同问题。在过去 18 个月中，声明 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/apr/19/florida-education-board-approves-expansion-dont-say-gay-bill&quot; >;包括佛罗里达州&lt;/a>;，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/north-carolina-lawmakers-override-veto-on-bill-limiting-lgbtq-instruction-in-early -grades&quot;>;北卡罗来纳州&lt;/a>;和&lt;a href=&quot;https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/4023336-iowa-governor-signs-bill-restricting-lessons-on-gender-identity- Sex-orientation-in-schools/&quot;>;爱荷华州&lt;/a>;已通过法案，限制教师在学校讨论性和性别认同的方式和时间。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;被问及美国的言论自由状况时，拉什迪说：“问题之一是，基本上只有一个主要政党似乎相信民主价值观。而另一个人似乎正在竭尽全力破坏他们。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“当绝大多数共和党选民相信上次选举被窃取时 - 就像他们每次选举时所做的那样问，绝大多数共和党选民认为唐纳德·特朗普赢得了上次选举，并且他的胜利被欺骗了 - 如果对真相的攻击达到了这种程度的成功，那么我们真的有麻烦了。”&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;1988 年，伊朗时任领导人阿亚图拉鲁霍拉·霍梅尼 (Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini) 的著作《撒旦诗篇》出版后，他发布了追杀令，要求处死拉什迪。伊斯兰。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;0d93d8347c7fcd6c9b8625f20a6292b4f126ca61&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/0d93d8347c7fcd6c9b8625f20a6292b4f126ca61/0_184_5760_34 56/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;一群人在舞台，是从阳台座位上拍摄的。” width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;这张来自视频的静止图像显示，哈迪·马塔尔（左）被护送下舞台，而人们则走向位于肖托夸研究所的萨尔曼·拉什迪（中右）。 Chautauqua, New York, 12 August 2022.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: AP&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;In August 2022 the 76-year-old was attacked in upstate New York as he prepared to speak at a literary event. Rushdie was stabbed in the neck and torso and spent six weeks in a hospital. The attack left him without sight in one eye and injuries to a hand, which makes typing difficult.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Speaking at the summit Wednesday, Rushdie criticized a “golden age myth,” which he said led to the rise of Trump and Brexit.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“&#39;Make America great again&#39; - that&#39;s always made me want to ask: &#39;When exactly was that?&#39; What is the date to which we are looking backwards? Was it, for example, when there was slavery? Was it before women had the right to vote? Was it before the civil rights movement?&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Exactly which is the American greatness to which we must return?”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Rushdie added:&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“And the thing about the golden age is that it never existed, and the myth of the golden age is always used to justify actions in the present.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“In England, the Brexit catastrophe was the result of another golden age myth, which is: &#39;England used to be this glorious country and it could be that glorious country again, if only we could get rid of all these foreigners.&#39;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Of course they neglected to mention to the electorate that the reason England was so prosperous was that it had spent 200 years plundering the rest of the world.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In May Rushdie made his first public appearance since the attack in New York, and has since &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/jun/01/salman-rushdie-to-write-a-book-about-being-stabbed-on-stage&quot;>;said&lt;/a>; he plans to write a book about the incident.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Hadi Matar, from New Jersey, was charged with attempted second-degree murder and second-degree assault in the attack. The 24-year-old has pleaded not guilty.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 09:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Austrian ex-foreign minister moves to Russia – with ponies flown in on military plane]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/14/karin-kneissl-austria-ex-foreign-minister-moves-to-russia]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T00:45:53Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/414ba2186d3a58d3c226550a705bef8580fb596d/0_259_4707_2823/master/4707.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=82a11859239c5000fadc49424f2de83a&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Then Austrian foreign minister Karin Kneissl dances with Russian president Vladimir Putin at her wedding in August 2018.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;An Austrian former foreign minister, Karin Kneissl, who became infamous in 2018 for &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/18/cossacks-flowers-putin-austria-wedding-dance&quot;>;dancing with Russian president Vladimir Putin at her wedding&lt;/a>;, has moved to St Petersburg – along with her ponies, which were flown in on a Russian military plane.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In 2018, Karin Kneissl, then foreign minister of neutral Austria, made headlines when she invited Putin to her wedding. It drew widespread criticism, coming just months after some EU countries – excluding Austria – expelled scores of Russian diplomats in response to the &lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/uk-news/sergei-skripal&quot;>;nerve agent attack on Sergei Skripal &lt;/a>;in Salisbury.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The 58-year-old left the government the following year. A highly controversial figure in her own country, Kneissl moved to France in September 2020 and became a guest columnist for &lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/russia&quot;>;Russia&lt;/a>; Today, which is widely viewed as a propaganda arm of the Kremlin.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In a Telegram post on Wednesday, she expressed astonishment that her move to Russia had become “political”, and said she had moved her “books, clothes and ponies from Marseille to Beirut via DHL” in June 2022 after being “banished” from France.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/may/19/gerhard-schroder-to-be-stripped-of-office-for-not-cutting-ties-with-russia&quot;>;Gerhard Schröder to be stripped of privileges for not cutting ties with Russia&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;But Lebanon was only a temporary solution, she said, and she travelled to Russia every six weeks for work, where she is now setting up a thinktank.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Due to sanctions there are neither flights nor DHL [for the move to Russia],” she wrote. “I therefore had the option of accompanying a Russian transport flight from Syria to Russia, for which I am very grateful.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Last week, Kneissl&#39;s two ponies were flown to St Petersburg on a military aircraft from the Russian air base at Hmeimim in Syria after it was diverted from carrying troops, according to a report by Russian investigative website &lt;a href=&quot;https://theins.ru/news/265002&quot;>;The Insider&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In June, Kneissl unveiled the Gorki centre – a thinktank attached to St Petersburg university to operate under her leadership. The thinktank was set up to “help define the policies for the Russian Federation” with a focus on the Near and Middle East.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In 2021, Kneissl &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jun/02/former-austrian-minister-given-seat-on-board-of-russias-rosneft&quot;>;joined the board of directors of the Russian oil giant Rosneft&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She stepped down in May 2022 after the European Parliament passed a resolution threatening sanctions against Europeans still on the boards of major Russian companies.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Agence France-Presse contributed to this report&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 09:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Musk, Zuckerberg and tech heavyweights convene in Washington for AI forum]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/13/tech-leaders-washington-ai-saferty-forum-elon-musk-zuckerberg-pichai]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T00:27:55Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/744ecef2f0e77400e54ca14bbfd1f09e01a142e5/0_353_6052_3632/master/6052.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=ac27fc226d2808beacf1ec978566fdd3&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Tech leaders attend the Senate bipartisan Artificial Intelligence (AI) Insight Forum on Capitol Hill.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;A delegation of top tech leaders including Sundar Pichai, Elon Musk, Mark Zuckerberg and Sam Altman convened in Washington on Wednesday for a closed-door meeting with US senators to discuss the rise of artificial intelligence and how it should be regulated.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jul/20/artificial-intelligence-us-elections&quot;>;&#39;An evolution in propaganda&#39;: a digital expert on AI influence in elections&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;The discussion, billed as an “AI safety forum”, is one of several meetings between Silicon Valley, researchers, labor leaders and government and is taking on fresh urgency with the US elections looming and the rapid pace of AI advancement already affecting peoples&#39; lives and work.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Democratic senator Chuck Schumer, who called the meeting “historic”, said that attendees loosely endorsed the idea of regulations but that there is little consensus on what such rules would look like.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Schumer said he asked everyone in the room – including more than 60 senators, almost two dozen tech executives, advocates and skeptics – whether government should have a role in the oversight of artificial intelligence, and that “every single person raised their hands, even though they had diverse views”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Among the ideas discussed was whether there should be an independent agency to oversee certain aspects of the rapidly-developing technology, how companies could be more transparent and how the US can stay ahead of China and other countries.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The key point was really that it&#39;s important for us to have a referee,” said Elon Musk, the CEO of Tesla and X, the social network formerly known as Twitter, during a break in the forum. “It was a very civilized discussion, actually, among some of the smartest people in the world.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Congress should do what it can to maximize the benefits and minimize the negatives of AI, Schumer &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/SenSchumer/status/1702047942679433647?s=20&quot;>;told reporters&lt;/a>;, “whether that&#39;s enshrining bias, or the loss of jobs, or even the kind of doomsday scenarios that were mentioned in the room. And only government can be there to put in guardrails”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Attendees also discussed the pressing need for steps to protect the 2024 US elections from &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jul/20/artificial-intelligence-us-elections&quot;>;disinformation becoming supercharged by AI&lt;/a>;, Schumer said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The issue of actually having deep fakes where people really believe that somebody, that a campaign was saying something when they were the total creation of AI” was a key concern, said Schumer, and that “watermarking” – badging content as AI generated – was discussed as a solution.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;99cf85a1df6b06898acbb5338d2f8cdd9a94daf9&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/99cf85a1df6b06898acbb5338d2f8cdd9a94daf9/0_0_4451_2967/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;US Senate majority leader Chuck Schumer speaks to members of the press.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;667&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;US Senate majority leader Chuck Schumer speaks to members of the press.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Alex Wong/Getty Images&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Several AI experts and other industry leaders also attended, including Bill Gates; the Motion Picture Association CEO Charles Rivkin; the former Google CEO Eric Schmidt; the Center for Humane Technology co-founder Tristan Harris; and Deborah Raji, a researcher at University of California, Berkeley.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Some labor and civil liberties groups were also represented among the 22 attendees including Elizabeth Shuler, the president of the labor union AFL-CIO;美国教师联合会主席兰迪·温加滕（Randi Weingarten）；珍妮特·穆尔吉亚 (Janet Murguía)，UnidosUS 主席； and Maya Wiley, the president and CEO of the Leadership Conference on Civil &amp;amp; Human Rights.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sparked by the release of ChatGPT less than a year ago, businesses have been clamoring to apply new generative AI tools that can compose human-like passages of text, program computer code and create novel images, audio and video. The hype over such tools has accelerated worries over its potential societal harms and prompted calls for more transparency in how the data behind the new products is collected and used.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In his opening remarks, which Meta shared with the Guardian, Mark Zuckerberg said the company is working with academics, policy makers and civil society to “minimize the risk” of the technology while ensuring they don&#39;t undervalue the benefits. He specifically cited work on how to watermark AI content to avoid risks such as mass spread of disinformation.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Before the forum, representatives for the Alphabet Workers Union said that Schuler, the president of AFL-CIO, would raise worker issues including those of AI raters – human moderators who are tasked with training, testing and evaluating results from Google Search and the company&#39;s AI chatbot – who say they have struggled with low wages and minimum benefits.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“There are many conversations still to come and, throughout the process, the interests of working people must be Congress&#39; North Star,” Schuler said in a statement. “Workers are not the victims of technological change– – we&#39;re the solution.”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;31acbb687a148a054f38df460e09743c03084fd1&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/31acbb687a148a054f38df460e09743c03084fd1/0_0_4000_2667/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Meredith Stiehm, the president of Writers Guild of America (WGA), and Randi Weingarten, the president of American Federation of Teachers.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;667&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Meredith Stiehm, the president of Writers Guild of America (WGA), and Randi Weingarten, the president of American Federation of Teachers.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Shutterstock&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;While Schumer described the meeting as “diverse”, the sessions faced criticism for leaning heavily on the opinions of people who stand to benefit from the rapid advancements in generative AI technology. “Half of the people in the room represent industries that will profit off lax AI regulations,” said Caitlin Seeley George, a campaigns and managing director at Fight for the Future, a digital rights group.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“People who are actually impacted by AI must have a seat at this table, including the vulnerable groups already being harmed by discriminatory use of AI right now,” George said. “Tech companies have been running the AI game long enough and we know where that takes us – biased algorithms that discriminate against Black and brown folks, immigrants, people with disabilities and other marginalized groups in banking, the job market, surveillance and policing.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Some senators were critical of the private meeting, arguing that tech executives should testify in public. The Republican senator Josh Hawley said he would not attend what he said was a “giant cocktail party for big tech”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I don&#39;t know why we would invite all the biggest monopolists in the world to come and give Congress tips on how to help them make more money and then close it to the public,” Hawley said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Agencies contributed reporting&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 08:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Jong-un invites Putin to North Korea after summit brings ties to ‘a new level’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/14/kim-jong-un-invites-vladimir-putin-to-north-korea]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-14T00:06:26Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a674db84adc255599a03b337977a9265843fccfe/232_100_3628_2179/master/3628.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=5ed648a4b6e9329032aa1c297972e3e1&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;North Korean leader Kim Jong-un meets Russia&#39;s president Vladimir Putin at the Vostochny cosmodrome in Russia&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Kim Jong-un invited President Vladimir Putin to visit North Korea during their meeting in Russia on Wednesday, Pyongyang&#39;s state media reported, amid warnings that Kim was poised to offer the Kremlin artillery shells and other munitions for the war in Ukraine.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kim told Putin that their closely watched meeting had brought bilateral ties to a new level, and expressed his willingness to foster stable, future-oriented relations for the next 100 years, news agency KCNA said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The report went on to say that Kim was briefed on technical details about Russian space vehicles &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/kim-jong-un-putin-weapons-talk-russian-space-base-amur&quot;>;during his visit to a cosmodrome&lt;/a>;, but there was no mention of any arms supplies, trade of weapons or technical assistance over weapons programs.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Japan&#39;s Kyodo news agency quoted sources saying Kim was scheduled to visit a factory that manufactures Sukhoi fighter jets and other aircraft after the talks with Putin.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/nothing-left-to-lose-putin-embraces-role-of-spoiler-with-kim-jong-un-summit&quot;>;&#39;Nothing left to lose&#39;: Putin embraces role of spoiler with Kim Jong-un summit&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;US and South Korean officials have expressed concern that Kim could provide weapons and ammunition to Russia, which has expended vast stocks in more than 18 months of war in Ukraine. Moscow and Pyongyang have denied such intentions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;On Wednesday, Putin gave numerous hints that military cooperation was discussed at the summit, but disclosed few details.俄罗斯国防部长绍伊古出席了会谈。 The Kremlin said sensitive discussions between neighbours were a private matter.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;During Wednesday&#39;s meeting at the Vostochny cosmodrome in the remote region of Amur, Kim offered Putin his support for Russia&#39;s “sacred fight” against the west, while Putin reportedly offered Russian help with North Korea&#39;s troubled satellite programme.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The two leaders&#39; one-on-one talks, as well as discussions with delegations, lasted for about two hours and were followed by an official dinner in Kim&#39;s honour. The two also discussed the possibility of sending a North Korean cosmonaut into space, said Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The choice of venue for the summit was significant, given North Korea&#39;s interest in pursuing a space programme. Before their talks, the leaders toured assembly and launch facilities at the cosmodrome, located in the forests of eastern Russia, not far from the Chinese border.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-interactive=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/embed/iframe-wrapper/0.1/boot.js&quot; data-canonical-url=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/uploader/embed/2023/09/embed-2023-09-13t140153-196-zip/giv-13425KHiL2MioMmLm&quot; data-alt=&quot;locator map&quot;>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/uploader/embed/2023/09/embed-2023-09-13t140153-196-zip/giv-13425KHiL2MioMmLm&quot;>;Interactive&lt;/a>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;On Wednesday, the US expressed alarm over potential new military cooperation between Russia and North Korea. The cooperation announced during Kim&#39;s visit was “quite troubling and would potentially be in violation of multiple UN security council resolutions”, state department spokesperson Matthew Miller said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He noted US concerns that North Korean satellites, on which president Putin promised cooperation, have been used to develop Pyongyang&#39;s ballistic missiles.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The US “will not hesitate” to impose sanctions if appropriate, Miller said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The US secretary of state, Antony Blinken, said in an interview aired on Wednesday that Russia&#39;s reliance on North Korea and Iran showed its dire situation as it wages its war in Ukraine.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“That&#39;s kind of a &#39;Star Wars&#39; bar scene of countries. So I think it does speak to Russia&#39;s desperation,” Blinken told the Pod Save the World podcast.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“We&#39;re looking to make sure that we, as necessary, can impose costs and consequences.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Separately on Wednesday, the US approved a $5bn sale to South Korea of F-35s, top-of-the-line fighter-jets with stealth capacity.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The sale of the 25 jets “will improve the Republic of Korea&#39;s capability to meet current and future threats by providing credible defense capability to deter aggression in the region and ensure interoperability with US forces”, a state department statement said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The sale comes as tensions with North Korea ratchet up. Pyongyang carried out its latest missile tests as Kim visited Russia.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The US has stepped up three-way cooperation with Japan and South Korea, allies that are home to US troops. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/17/us-promises-new-era-as-biden-prepares-to-host-first-summit-with-japan-and-south-korea&quot;>;At a summit last month at the Camp David presidential resort&lt;/a>; near Washington, President Joe Biden, South Korea&#39;s President Yoon Suk Yeol and the Japanese prime minister, Fumio Kishida, promised to work more closely together on North Korea and other challenges.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;With Agence France-Presse and Reuters&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 08:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Republican congresswoman kicked out of musical for ‘causing disturbance’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/13/lauren-boebert-kicked-out-beetlejuice]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-13T21:47:01Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/15f555dd4ac1d6b36293b47bc6d157cdb0ec14d1/0_0_6194_3718/master/6194.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=a09e844a4331cfa958962a6c985af0a5&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Lauren Boebert&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;The US congresswoman Lauren Boebert was kicked out of a performance of the musical Beetlejuice in Denver on Sunday, according to security footage.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The theater didn&#39;t name Boebert, but a spokesperson said on Wednesday that the video – which showed Boebert and a guest being escorted out of the venue – was of guests who were kicked out after audience members accused them of vaping, singing, using phones and causing a disturbance.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/13/mitt-romney-retirement-trump&quot;>;Mitt Romney condemns &#39;demagogue&#39; Trump as he announces retirement&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Her campaign manager confirmed that Boebert was kicked out but denies she was vaping. Boebert and the other guest left.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I can confirm the stunning and salacious rumors: in her personal time, congresswoman Lauren Boebert is indeed a supporter of the performing arts (gasp!),” said Drew Sexton, Boebert&#39;s campaign manager, in a text message, adding that Boebert “pleads guilty to singing along, laughing and enjoying herself”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Boebert is in her second term in Congress and is running for re-election in Colorado&#39;s third congressional district, largely covering the state&#39;s western half. The theater disturbance was first reported by the Denver Post.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In her relatively short time in Washington DC, Boebert has built a national profile with a combative style that has grabbed media headlines, most famously by heckling President Joe Biden during his 2022 State of the Union address to Congress.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;During the argument in the theater, the two made comments along the lines of “do you know who I am” and “I will be contacting the mayor,” according to the venue&#39;s statement.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;On the social media platform X, formerly known as Twitter, Boebert said: “Everyone should go see it if you get a chance this week and please let me know how it ends!”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The two guests at first refused to leave the venue, even after an employee threatened to get the police, the theater said in a statement. Once a police officer was on the way, the two left, the theater said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The security footage provided to the Associated Press does not appear to show Boebert vaping.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 07:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Mexican senate hears testimony on extraterrestrial life: ‘We are not alone’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/13/mexican-senate-hearing-ufos]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-13T22:21:38Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3162c5000b794f07fbcced2fb17182566439088d/0_3_1600_960/master/1600.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=72d0896ca75d1608ab3f8aacaac51a3f&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;A group of international experts hold a hearing in Mexico&#39;s lower house to discuss extraterrestrial sightings in Mexico City, Mexico on Wednesday.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Mexican senators have heard testimony that “we are not alone” in the universe and been presented with the alleged remains of “non-human” mummies, in the country&#39;s first official event on extraterrestrial life.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;At a senate hearing on Tuesday, lawmakers were shown two shriveled bodies with shrunken heads – alongside video footage of “unexplained anomalous phenomena” – by Jaime Maussan, a former sports journalist-turned UFO-enthusiast.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Maussan said the remains were more than 1,000 years old and belonged to “non-human beings that are not part of our terrestrial evolution”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It&#39;s the queen of all evidence,” Maussan claimed. “That is, if the DNA is showing us that they are non-human beings and that there is nothing that looks like this in the world, we should take it as such.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Other studies have suggested the mummies, which were found in Nazca, Peru, in 2017, are fraudulent.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Tuesday&#39;s hearing was organised by Sergio Gutiérrez Luna, a lawmaker from the governing Morena party and aspiring governor of the state of Veracruz.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jul/17/mexico-hurricanes-alien-base-gulf-coast&quot;>;Space oddity: Mexican group claims alien base offers hurricane protection&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;It included participants from around the world who made calls for transparency and international cooperation. Maussan suggested that Mexico could become the first country in the world to accept the presence of aliens on the planet.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Gutiérrez Luna said that Congress had not taken a position on the theories put forward during the hearing but stressed the important of listening to “all voices, all opinions”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The event was inspired by the US congressional hearing on the same topic in July, in which the retired Major David Grusch &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jul/26/ufo-hearing-congress-evidence-david-grusch&quot;>;alleged that the US was hiding a program to retrieve and reverse engineer UFOs.&lt;/a>; The Pentagon has denied his claims.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In media interviews, Grusch has made even more outlandish claims that the US government has in its possession the bodies of “&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/MickWest/status/1665852276093730818&quot;>;dead pilots&lt;/a>;” and &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/MickWest/status/1666544299042017280&quot;>;a flying saucer&lt;/a>; found in Italy by Mussolini almost 100 years ago.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Nonetheless the congressional hearing was a sign of the increased respectability of a field once seen as the reserve of conspiracy theorists.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Well-known politicians, such as Republican senator Marco Rubio, have pushed for more disclosure, and in 2022 Barack Obama told CBS that the government has “footage and records of objects in the skies, that we don&#39;t know exactly what they are, we can&#39;t explain how they moved, their trajectory”.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 14 Sep 2023 06:52:01 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>